                    <h3 class="post-title"><a title="[Interview] How to reach 154% of its goal on KickStarter?" href="http://seedingfactory.com/2012/10/interview-tribute-games/">[Interview] How to reach 154% of its goal on KickStarter?</a></h3>
                    <div class="entry">
                        <p><strong>[&#8230;]</strong><strong></strong></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>S.F. : What was the biggest milestone during the campaign ?</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>J.L.</strong>: In term of hype, I think that the announcement of a second playable character was the biggest milestone. But personally, the biggest moment was when we reached our goal because it secured the future of our project.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>S.F. : Can you portray briefly the type of people who backed your game ?</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>J.L.</strong>: We don&#8217;t have that much information to portray our backers, but it seems to be  varied. Obviously, most of them are certainly gamers but we received messages from people of various backgrounds and even some kids too young to be eligible to Kickstarter wrote to us and told us that they would have liked to support us.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>SF : Retrospectively what was your 3 best assets for running this successful campaign ? What was the 3 things you will do differently ?</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>J.L.</strong>:</p>
<ol start="1">
<li>Being well prepared. We did well in taking our time in building a great Kickstarter page. We could have done it even <strong>better if we had better planned our launch</strong> though. We launched our page the same day as the <a href="http://www.gamescom-cologne.com/en/gamescom/home/index.php">Gamescom</a>, so game journalists were already busy with big announcements when we asked them to talk about our campaign.</li>
<li>We did a decent job in promoting it. We used social networks the best we could and we had <a href="http://probertson.tumblr.com/">Paul Robertson</a> and <a href="http://radiomaru.tumblr.com/">Bryan Lee O&#8217;Malley</a> posting about it on their respective Tumblr. And constant updates were a must. I think most successful Kickstarter campaigns usually have bigger fan bases on their social networks than what we had to start with. We almost started from nothing, so it would have been better to start promoting Mercenary Kings <strong>BEFORE launching</strong> our Kickstarter page.</li>
<li><strong>Our first reward was the actual game</strong> which was tangible enough to convince a lot of backers. Our rewards were not perfect though and we had a lot of suggestions along the way, so we could probably have divided mid-tier rewards better.</li>
</ol>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>S.F. : You announced a  partnership with OUYA, how did it happen ?</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>J.L</strong>.: We really like the OUYA. Jean-François and I both <a href="http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/ouya/ouya-a-new-kind-of-video-game-console?ref=live">backed it on Kickstarter</a>. Also, the OUYA will be completely opened to indie developers, so it&#8217;s not like we&#8217;ll need to find a publisher or buy an expensive license to publish a game on OUYA.</p>
<p>However, there were two problems to solve before confirming that we&#8217;d be able to port Mercenary Kings to OUYA. The first problem was the technology, our game engine currently doesn&#8217;t work on Android, so we had to figure out how we were gonna make it work. The second condition was to be able to distribute free OUYA keys  to our backers. So, we had to contact the OUYA team about this before announcing anything.</p>
<p><strong>Both problems were solved, so we announced it</strong>!</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>S.F.: To conclude, do you have any comment about the Crowdfunding experience ?</strong></span></p>
<p><strong>J.L</strong>.: It&#8217;s wonderful for indie games, and I&#8217;m glad that we had the chance to have this when starting up our company. However, it was the most stressful and time consuming experience I&#8217;ve had in a long time.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<hr style="color: #ef6318; background-color: #ef6318; height: 1px;" />
<h5>A huge thanks to Jonathan and the Tribute Game team for this excellent interview.</h5>
<h4>You could meet them @ MIGS (Montreal, 12-15 Nov 2012) in the DEMO Zone.</h4>
